metadata.name: caravans #345
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by Paul Klee's 'Zwei Kamele und ein Esel' (Two camels and a donkey), abacuses and excessive shopping sprees.

An anonymous caravan makes its way through abstract deserts, carrying their semi-brutalist cargo towards an unknown destination.

All primary proceeds go to the Processing foundation.

Happy birthday fxhash!

Written in JavaScript, rendering to Canvas.

metadata.name: Pines #49
metadata.description:
A combination of pine trees, hills and mountains put together in a way that represents nature in it's true form.

Everything is generated by code by drawing pixels on a canvas using Javascript.
The simplex-noise library was used to generate the hills and the mountains.

I hope you like this piece!

metadata.description: "Lime Brass Hyacinth" is a p5.js project where isometric shapes are placed and have their size and color adjusted based on an underlying grid of gradients. metadata.name: CA Class 3 #124
metadata.description:
CA Class 3 is a family of cellular automata (CA) drawing algorithms.  Each algorithm generates a pattern procedurally from the top row down using a simple set of rules.  The top row of cells is seeded using the fxhash id, and a drawing rule is chosen at random.  The drawing rules themselves never change, but variation across the color palettes, cell sizes, and rule set selections produces a variety of textures.

Class 3 cellular automatons produce randomness.  All of the class 3 rules’ patterns are self-similar - lots of little triangles and branching patterns of varying sizes - but they do not repeat or settle into orderly behavior.  They are analogous to irrational numbers like pi that go on forever.  

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

Props and attribution to Stephen Wolfram, Johnny Von Nuemann and Nils Aall Barricelli

metadata.name: Maroon Nickel Butterfly #142
metadata.description:
"Maroon Nickel Butterfly" is a p5.js project where isometric shapes are placed and have their size and color adjusted based on an underlying image taken from Adolphe Millot's Papillons. Each form gets its color and size from a particular pixel. Giving the isometric forms a slight wiggle provides the piece with a more painterly feel.

Adolphe Millot on Wikipedia https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolphe_Philippe_Millot

metadata.name: The Song Of Colors #63
metadata.description:
Watercolor painting was my favorite technique for playing. I love combining colors, merging and blending them together. Furthermore, I started experimenting with large pieces of canvas, placed them at different heights, and poured vast layers of acrylic fluid paint on them.
The energy of these paintings is incredible. As I layer the colors, the colors begin to converse. It seems to have the color of its own mind.
I started with an image in mind, but always, painting takes over everything. Using canvas installed at different heights requires careful thinking and planning in advance. Sometimes the color goes into a new shape that I did not expect, but I correct it and use it to the fullest. This kind of art creates exciting and psychological paintings!
Color flow is instantaneous. I am constantly spinning around the canvas and directing the flow; there is no time but to go with the flow. I started as a guide, but I know that I've just been an active agent - letting the song of colors sing and flow.
- Press "S" to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.
Made with p5js.
